From c07453c4ed8c63b030a9e1a2e9ad18f55f6f683f Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Wed, 4 Mar 2026 22:40:30 +0100
Subject: [PATCH 001/174] PGCL: Page clustering (larpage) forward-port to Linux
 6.19

Decouple kernel PAGE_SIZE from hardware MMUPAGE_SIZE on x86_64.
When CONFIG_PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0, the kernel allocates physical memory
in PAGE_SIZE chunks (e.g. 16KB for PAGE_MMUSHIFT=2) while mapping
individual MMUPAGE_SIZE (4KB) PTEs to userspace.

Core infrastructure:
- Add MMUPAGE_SIZE/MMUPAGE_SHIFT/MMUPAGE_MASK definitions
- PAGE_SIZE = MMUPAGE_SIZE << PAGE_MMUSHIFT
- Add pte_cluster.h for multi-PTE fault handling
- Add pgoff unit conversion helpers (page cache vs VMA units)

x86_64 changes:
- Boot sequence: identity mapping, trampoline, early page tables
- CPA (Change Page Attribute): page_level_shift() uses MMUPAGE_SHIFT
- clear_page/copy_page: operate on PAGE_SIZE bytes
- VDSO, fixmap, CPU entry area: MMUPAGE-aware

MM subsystem:
- vm_pgoff is in MMUPAGE units (supports sub-PAGE mmap offsets)
- All PTE walkers step by MMUPAGE_SIZE (vmscan, swapfile, mlock,
  memory-failure, rmap, procfs)
- Userspace syscall alignment: mmap, mlock, msync, mprotect, mremap,
  brk use MMUPAGE_MASK/MMUPAGE_ALIGN
- procfs: smaps RSS/PSS accounting per MMUPAGE, pagemap interface
  with MMUPAGE granularity
- Rmap: folio_within_range/vma_address handle PAGE/MMUPAGE unit
  conversion via pgoff_page_to_mmu()/pgoff_to_vma_addr()

Subsystem fixes:
- ELF loader: ELF_EXEC_PAGESIZE = MMUPAGE_SIZE (AT_PAGESZ = 4096)
- perf: ring buffer mmap fault handler for MMUPAGE pgoff
- uprobes, BPF stackmap: vm_pgoff << MMUPAGE_SHIFT
- secretmem, relay: vmf->pgoff conversion

Status: PAGE_MMUSHIFT=2 (16KB pages) boots to busybox userspace
on QEMU x86_64 SMP=4. W+X mapping check passes.

Based on Hugh Dickins' original "larpage" patch (2001) and
William Lee Irwin III's PGCL patches (2002-2004).

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>
